item.title: Canadian Prime Minister Appoints New Finance Minister
item.description: Canadian Prime Minister Justin Trudeau named his deputy, Chrystia Freeland, as the country’s new finance minister and said he would suspend parliament until Sept. 23 as he attempts to turn the page on conflict-of-interest allegations that have weighed heavily on his support this summer.

item.title: Putin Warns European Leaders to Keep Out of Belarus Crisis
item.description: Russian President Vladimir Putin warned top European leaders against interfering in the political crisis engulfing Russia’s longtime ally, Belarus, as protests against its leader continue to swell.

item.title: Sudan in Talks to Formalize Ties With Israel
item.description: Israel and Sudan said that they are working on an agreement to formalize relations, in the latest sign of warmer ties between Arab nations and a former enemy.

item.title: Soldiers Detain Mali Leaders in Apparent Coup Attempt
item.description: Mutineering soldiers in Mali detained President Ibrahim Boubacar Keita, Prime Minister Boubou Cisse and dozens of other senior officials in what appeared to be a coup attempt after months of demonstrations calling for the government’s resignation.

item.title: China's Xi Jinping Tightens Grip on Domestic Security Forces in First Broad Purge
item.description: The Chinese leader has unleashed a clean-up of the country’s powerful domestic-security apparatus, indicating he is facing thorny concerns at home.

item.title: Tribunal Convicts Hezbollah Member in Hariri Assassination, Acquits Three Others
item.description: An international tribunal convicted a member of Hezbollah of terrorism and homicide over the assassination of Lebanon’s former Prime Minister Rafik Hariri in 2005 but acquitted three others and found no evidence the group’s leadership was involved in the plot.
